The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan was inspired this time by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company created a robot that, by imitating the theft of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Advanced Technical Centre at Nissan Motor Co. made this little robot in collaboration with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Centre at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan Security Shield.
This robot will allow the brand's vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee created its own personal space of an oval shape that looks much like the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important is the compound eyes of the bee, able to see in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to steal without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects the obstacles that are within a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"When he detects an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by forging his wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape manoeuvre is totally instinctive.
If that were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Travel Laboratory and Senior Engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted upwards or downwards, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
" Each second of this device must only process information and act according to that data.
It does not need to retain the information or intuitive logics of prior manoeuvres, that is why it can operate continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise us, but we are not talking about giga-bytes of memory, not even mega-bytes."
This represents the first because of the development of new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced into the series cars in about ten years after Nissan.
The robot runs with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
