A fox in the chicken
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate on the basis of information on their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes that link the use of information concerning the prescription of medicinal products, in all cases, to the agreement of the person concerned.
This type of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is to entrust its chicken to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage the prescriptions of drugs, in Washington Post.
Insurance companies rely on insurance premiums and insured capital in the event of damage, the customer's health status, and if they feel that the risk is too great, they do not even secure it.
In the past, they sent candidates to medical examinations, and they signed insurance contracts with them only after they learned of the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much less expensive procedure: from an identification number, he provides himself easily at the pharmacy, the data concerning the purchase of drugs from the person within the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines himself, what disease the person is suffering and what his health is.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high rate of fat in the blood, which immediately puts it in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk factor, so there is nothing left to do to the insurer other than the paperwork. However, small problems may still arise.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or against heat sprays, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in data research and analysis, and they must seek permission from the patient before collecting necessary information from the pharmacy.
They are now under pressure from the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their past failures.
In recent years, some companies have also been dealing with the results of laboratory analyses, linking them with the data on drug use, thus providing an even more accurate picture of the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of use is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on the extension of the control circle of authorities concerning companies specializing in the supply of data is currently before the Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her agreement or not, since if he or she refuses, insurance does not sign an insurance contract with her.
Thus and finally, hens depend on the goodness of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are multiplying their trade by two.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global problems.
Today, there will also be a summit in France-India, where cooperation on atomic energy will be the main issue.
The European Union recognizes that India is a great emerging democratic power to which a broader right of speech should be given in international affairs, but the member countries have not yet succeeded in agreeing on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not focus too much on this issue yesterday at the 9th summit in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, like the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they were going to multiply trade by two, which means an increase of a good hundred billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, the exchange of goods has increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be too ambitious.
In this regard, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civil flights, and in this way air trade can also expand in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, which is the EU's first trading partner, and New Delhi, which is only ninth among EU partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The Afghan and Pakistani situation was strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and there was an urgent need to hold a United Nations conference on this issue.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been requested, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains faithful to the energy and climate programme, in particular that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least twenty per cent by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as the need for a global market to be made at the next year's climate conference, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 per cent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent the rise in food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian Head of State is now visiting the French capital, where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to press agency information, the agreement would cover 15 years.
